most likely affected by the disc herniation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C6","T1","C7","C8","C5"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECervical intervertebral discs typically compress the nerve root that exits at the level below the disc, because cervical nerve roots leave the canal above their corresponding vertebra except for C8, which exits between C7 and T1. A C5/6 disc herniation most often impinges the C6 nerve root.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture in the stem aligns with C6 radiculopathy: pain radiating to the thumb and index finger, weakness of wrist extension, and a reduced biceps reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC6\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because a C5/6 disc protrusion compresses the traversing C6 root, producing the described sensory, motor, and reflex changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC5\u003C/strong\u003E would be more likely with a C4/5 disc lesion and typically causes shoulder pain, deltoid weakness, and a reduced deltoid (C5) reflex, not the pattern described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC7\u003C/strong\u003E is classically affected by a C6/7 disc lesion with pain to the middle finger, triceps weakness, and reduced triceps reflex, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC8\u003C/strong\u003E involvement often produces symptoms in the ring and little fingers and weakness of finger flexors and intrinsic hand muscles; it is usually affected by a C7/T1 disc lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET1\u003C/strong\u003E radiculopathy primarily affects intrinsic hand muscles and the medial forearm sensation and is not typically caused by a C5/6 disc herniation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical disc herniations at C5/6 typically compress the C6 nerve root due to its exit below the C6 vertebra.","C6 radiculopathy commonly causes pain to the thumb and index finger, weakness of wrist extension, and a reduced biceps reflex."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98696"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98696"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T14:32:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:32:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10905"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116709"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medi